The surname is now widespread throughout England, but most common in Yorkshire. Compare   Belmont  .","History: Many English bearers of this surname are descended from Henry de Beaumont (died 1340), who came to England from France as a soldier, serving Kings Edward I, II, and III of England. He acquired the earldom of Buchan in Scotland by marriage. — Many American bearers of this surname are descendants of John Beaumont (1612–47), who came to North America from England in 1630. William Beaumont came from England to Cambridge MA in 1635 and subsequently moved to CT."],"variants":[{"name":"Bement","meanings":["English (Cambridgeshire): variant of   Beaumont  . This surname is now rare in Britain."]},{"name":"Beeman","meanings":["English (Kent): occupational name for a beekeeper, from Middle English <i>bee-man</i> ‘bee-keeper’ (Old English <i>bēo</i> + <i>mann</i>).","English (Kent): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German   Biemann   or of its Dutch cognate <b>Bieman</b>."]},{"name":"Belmont","meanings":["French and English (of Norman origin): variant of   Beaumont  .","Catalan: habitational name from the placename Bellmont ‘beautiful mountain’. Compare Spanish   Belmonte  ."]},{"name":"Baumunk","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Siegmund.","German: probably a Germanized form of a French Huguenot name <b>Beaumont</b> (see also   Beaumont  )."]},{"name":"Bayman","meanings":["English (mainly Lancashire): variant of   Beaumont  .","Americanized form of German <b>Beumann</b> or <b>Bäumann</b>, variants of   Baumann  ."]}]},{"name":"Ivo","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Form of   Yves   used in Germany and occasionally in the English-speaking world. It represents the nominative case of the Latinized form of the name."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ivo Bellomontensis de Beaumont was born in 1026, in Cotentin, Normandy, France, his father, Hughes d